First, convert the radius to centimeters: \[ R_{\mathrm{WD}} = 10^4 \text{ km} = 10^9 \text{ cm} \] Next, compute \( R^2 \): \[ R^2 = (10^9 \text{ cm})^2 = 10^{18} \text{ cm}^2 \] Compute \( T^4 \): \[ T^4 = (5 \times 10^4 \text{ K})^4 = 6.25 \times 10^{18} \text{ K}^4 \] Substitute the values into the Stefan-Boltzmann law: \[ L = 4\pi \times 10^{18} \text{ cm}^2 \times 5.67 \times 10^{-5} \text{ erg/s/cm}^2/\text{K}^4 \times 6.25 \times 10^{18} \text{ K}^4 \] Calculate step-by-step: 1. Compute \( 4\pi \): \[ 4\pi \approx 12.566 \] 2. Multiply the constants: \[ 12.566 \times 5.67 \times 10^{-5} \approx 7.125 \times 10^{-4} \] 3. Multiply by \( 10^{18} \times 6.25 \times 10^{18} \): \[ 7.125 \times 10^{-4} \times 6.25 \times 10^{36} \approx 4.453 \times 10^{33} \text{ erg/s} \] Round to two significant figures: \[ 4.453 \times 10^{33} \text{ erg/s} \approx 4.5 \times 10^{33} \text{ erg/s} \] Thus, the luminosity of the white dwarf is \(\boxed{4.5 \times 10^{33}}\) erg/s.
